  "texts": [
    "Unlike traditional definitions rooted in generator design specifications, we adopt an empirical view of inertia based on how a region Interconnection frequency Measurements from WA,CO,AZ,UT,NM,MT,ID Measurements from CA Fig. 2.",
    "Frequency response of the U.S. Western Interconnection during a generation trip in CAISO.physically reacts to a sudden power imbalance.",
    "In this study, regional inertia is defined as the ability of a localized portion of the grid to resist frequency acceleration immediately following a disturbance.",
    "It is not inferred from static system models, but extracted directly from measurements of frequency and power imbalance during real-world events.To formalize this concept, consider the response of a region to a disturbance with a known power mismatch ∆P.",
    "The immediate RoCoF observed within the area, denoted as dfregion dt, is used to infer the region's effective inertia using the following rearranged form of the swing equation [9]:H region S region = ∆P • f s 2 • dfregion dt (1)where H region is the regional inertia constant, S region is the regional power capacity, f s is the nominal system frequency, f region is the regional frequency and ∆P is the active power mismatch."
  ]
}